The assignment constraint, i.e using only three matrices to compute the result, forces the use of a pointer swap to avoid copying memory unnecessarily. Therefore, instead of copying the result of the multiplication into a temporary buffer each time, two matrix pointers are used, and the result of the multiplication is swapped directly onto them.

In other words, this process reduces the complexity of copying the matrix from O(n²), to a simple assignment operation, O(1). In the literacy, it is called "double buffering".